@flexiarg futon-theory/derive-exits-on-a-minted-sorry
@title DERIVE Exits on a Minted Sorry (You Can't Argue Until You Know What You're Arguing About)
@sigils [∴/⊢?]
@keywords derive gate, typed sorry, hole-first, have-want arrow, phase exit, eightfold, Polish notation, BHK arrow, mission lifecycle
@audience anyone running the eightfold mission discipline, or building tooling that gates phase transitions
@tone foundational
@style pattern

! conclusion: The exit condition of DERIVE is a MINTED TYPED SORRY — an explicit (have → want) arrow, persisted (meme.arrow grain), naming the hole the rest of the mission exists to fill. No ARGUE until it exists: you cannot argue until you know what you are arguing about.

  + context: A mission opens with a free-form HEAD and a vague sense of gap
    (IDENTIFY), then charts what exists (MAP). The temptation at DERIVE is to
    start designing — assembling patterns, sketching solutions — with the hole
    still implicit, retrofitted later from whatever the design turned out to be.

  + IF:
      The eightfold sequence reaches DERIVE: context mapped, tension named
      loosely, and the next phase (ARGUE) wants to assemble a pattern cascade.

  + HOWEVER:
      Sorries are not handed to you on a golden plate. Identification is real
      work: the vague IDENTIFY-tension must be sharpened against the MAP into a
      typed hole — what we HAVE, what we WANT, and which gap-kind separates
      them. Skip it and ARGUE assembles a cascade around an unstated target;
      the problem node gets retrofitted (observed live: the first WM cascade,
      2026-06-12, was built ARGUE-first and its problem node back-filled);
      VERIFY then has no statement to witness against, and "advance the
      mission" has no operational meaning.

  + THEN:
      Gate the DERIVE → ARGUE transition on a minted sorry: an explicit
      (have → want) arrow with typed endpoints, persisted at the coarse grain
      (meme.arrow store; keyed by endpoints; :open with the construction named
      when one is known). In Polish-notation terms the sorry is the
      operator-head written FIRST; ARGUE's cascade is the operand tree built
      against it; VERIFY witnesses each application; INSTANTIATE evaluates.
      Tooling: the mission-scope detector can check the gate mechanically
      (DERIVE section present ∧ no sorry-arrow ⇒ phase-gate hole).

  + BECAUSE:
      Type before term is what makes the rest of the lifecycle composable: a
      cascade is only judgeable against a stated want (the ruling surface
      certifies problem → cascade → hole → solution as one chain); a witness
      only means something relative to a claim; and the WM's advance-typing
      (:ratified-car / :design / ...) is precisely a typing of OPEN SORRIES —
      none of which exist if DERIVE never minted one.

  + provenance: Joe, voice, 2026-06-12 17:23, WM piloted flight (fable-2
    pilot): "this sorry should be a gate at the end of the derive section —
    we can't go on to argue until we know what we're arguing about... We
    can't expect the sorrys to be handed us on a golden plate." First
    instance: arr-7535a5b6-e59 (M-first-flights INSTANTIATE hole), minted
    minutes before the ruling.
